ggplot(df, aes(x = rank, y = lowest_yearly_earnings)) +

Based on a lot of visualization works, we found that the earning data is highly unevenly distributed and hard to find the right thresholds. Visually, these data points can be divided into two piles. Most of data points are fall into higher levels, and another pile is channels with extremely low earnings.

This could cause problems when we turn the response variable into binary. If we just choose a threshold based on earnings distribution, then this variables are uneven, potentially causing poor performance of our models. On the other hand, If we choose median or mean value would directly cut off the high earnings pile, Conflicting with the high-and-low-income business logic. And there is no general criteria for youTube channels earning division. Its a dilemma to find the right threshold.

So hopefully we would expect the machine learning classification models would have a good result in later works.

Linear Regression Analysis and Important Outputs

Building on previous visualization work, we have learned that there is some linear correlation between earnings and the last 30 days views, so we first build an LM model to confirm this relationship.

lm_view_earning <- lm(lowest_yearly_earnings  ~ video_views_for_the_last_30_days, data = df)

# Visualize residuals vs. fitted values
plot(lm_view_earning, which = 1)

Here we see that linearity hold perfectly well, as the red line is overlapping with most dashed line. The outputs seem ideal, but raise many questions. The earnings data was very likely to be exported directly from an online youtube income calculator by the author of the dataset.

Such as Social Bladeis a website which is YouTube certified tracking user statistics for YouTube. According to its calculator, estimated daily earnings = daily views/1000 * estimated CPM (Note: The accepted formula that Social Blade LLC uses to calculate the CPM range is $0.25 USD - $4.00 USD.) CPM, or cost per 1,000 impressions, is the cost an advertiser needs to pay on YouTube for every 1,000 impressions their ads receive on the video. https://blog.hubspot.com/marketing/youtube-cpm

daily_views <- df$video_views_for_the_last_30_days / 30

estimated_daily_earnings <- daily_views / 1000 * 0.25   # income calculator formula
matching_threshold <- 50  

summary(abs(estimated_daily_earnings * 30 - df$lowest_monthly_earnings) <= matching_threshold)

estimated_daily_earnings_highest <- daily_views / 1000 * 4
summary(abs(estimated_daily_earnings_highest * 30 - df$highest_monthly_earnings) <= matching_threshold)
##    Mode   FALSE    TRUE    NA's

The results highly match to our previous guess, except that the highest CPM limit may be slightly different. And its explainable, because many factors come into play when calculating a CPM. Quality of traffic, source country, niche type of video, price of specific ads, adblock, the actual click rate, etc. For the lowest earning on the other hand is the ad revenue that a youTuber will certainly receive.

Platforms like YouTube have witnessed notable changes in the number and nature of advertisements accompanying videos. Due to the revenue-sharing model based on advertisements, YouTuber have to increase its video view count.(Irshad, Anand, and Ram 2023)

Now, we are clear why residuals vs.fitted values overlap And further independent variables selection shall not focus on views if we choose earnings as our target variable

As we understand earnings mainly come from advertisements, viewers engagements seem to be more important in terms of predicting earnings. Therefore we might need more information associated with those youTube channels.

0.7 Self-defined Function

# Function to count missing values in each column
count_missing <- function(data) {
  # Apply the is.na function to each column and calculate the sum of missing values
  sapply(data, FUN = function(col) sum(is.na(col)))
}

# Function to print the counts of missing values for columns with missing data
print_nacounts <- function(data) {
  # Get the counts of missing values for each column
  nacounts <- count_missing(data)
  # Identify columns with missing values
  hasNA <- which(nacounts > 0)
  
  # Create a data frame for printing
  na_df <- data.frame(Column = names(nacounts)[hasNA], Missing_Count = nacounts[hasNA])
  
  # Print the table
  #cat("Missing Value Counts:\n")
  print(na_df, row.names = FALSE)
}


# Change the dataframe where character columns to factors and return the dataframe
change_to_factor <- function(data) {
  df <- data %>%
    mutate_if(is.character, as.factor)
  
  return(df)
}

1.0 Pipline

prepration_pipeline <- function(data,feature_engineering_method=select_more) {
  prepared_data <- data |>
                  data_transformation_pipeline() |>
                  data_cleaning_pipeline() |>
                  feature_engineering_method()
  
  return(prepared_data)
}

data_transformation_pipeline <- function(data) {
  selected_data <- data |>
                  rename(education.enrollment = Gross.tertiary.education.enrollment....) |>
                  remove_columns() |>
                  merge_columns() |>
                  add_columns()
  
  return(selected_data)
}

data_cleaning_pipeline <- function(data) {
  cleaned_data <- data |>
                  # step 1: convert invalid values to NA
                  clean_invalid_data() |>
                  # step 2: dealing with missing values
                  drop_rows() |>
                  clean_categorical_data() |>
                  clean_numerical_data()
  
  return(cleaned_data)
}

merge_columns <- function(data) {
  merged_data <- data |>
  mutate(
    # Fill missing values in 'channel_type' using values from 'category'
    # create a new variable called channel_category
    channel_type = ifelse(channel_type == "nan", category, channel_type)
  )|>
    # Science & Technology -> Tech
    # Film & Animation -> film
    # Pets & Animals & ->
    # Howto & Style -> Howto
    # Shows ->  Entertainment
    # Gaming -> Games
    # People & Blogs -> People 
  mutate(
    channel_type = ifelse(channel_type == "Science & Technology", "Tech", channel_type),
    channel_type = ifelse(channel_type == "Film & Animation", "Film", channel_type),
    channel_type = ifelse(channel_type == "Pets & Animals", "Film", channel_type),
    channel_type = ifelse(channel_type == "Howto & Style", "Howto", channel_type),
    channel_type = ifelse(channel_type == "Shows", "Entertainment", channel_type),
    channel_type = ifelse(channel_type == "Gaming", "Games", channel_type),
    channel_type = ifelse(channel_type == "People & Blogs", "People", channel_type),
  ) |> select(-category) |> 
  filter(channel_type != "nan")
  
  return(merged_data)
}

clean_invalid_data <- function(data) {
  cleaned_data <-  mutate(data,
                # numerical variable
                # video views 0 -> NA
                video.views = na_if(video.views, 0),
                # created year 1970 -> NA
                created_year = na_if(created_year, 1970),
                # education.enrollment >100 -> NA
                education.enrollment =ifelse(education.enrollment > 100, NA, education.enrollment),
                # uploads == 0 -> NA
                uploads = na_if(uploads, 0)
                
                ) 
  #print_nacounts(data)
  return(cleaned_data)
}

  1. create a new category in categorical variables
clean_categorical_data <- function(data) {
  cleaned_data <- data %>%
  mutate(Country = ifelse(Country == "nan", 'missing', Country)) %>% 
  group_by(Country) %>%
  mutate(Country = ifelse(n() < 10, 'other', Country)) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  
# Replace 'channel_type' values with 'other' for counts less than 40
  group_by(channel_type) %>%
  mutate(channel_type = ifelse(n() < 10, 'other', channel_type)) %>%
  ungroup() |>
  change_to_factor()
  
  return(cleaned_data)
}

3.numerical missing values

Add uploads frequency by caculate two values

In this section, we calculate the uploads_frequency variable, which represents the number of uploads for one year.
This variable is derived from the existing data, specifically the uploads and created_year variables.

clean_numerical_data <- function(data,cleaning_method) {
  # Calculate time duration
current_year <- 2023

cleaned_data <- data |>
    mutate( age = current_year - created_year,
      uploads_frequency = uploads / age) |>
  within({
  # uploads_freq_cat
  uploads_freq_cat <- NA
  uploads_freq_cat[is.na(uploads_frequency)] <- "missing"
  uploads_freq_cat[uploads_frequency < 10] <- "low"
  uploads_freq_cat[uploads_frequency >= 10 & uploads_frequency <= 1000] <- "middle"
  uploads_freq_cat[uploads_frequency > 1000] <- "high"
  uploads_frequency[is.na(uploads_frequency)] <- 0
  
  # subscriber_increase_rate
  subscriber_increase_rate[is.na(subscriber_increase_rate)] <- 0
  
  # Country information
  Population[is.na(Population)] <- 0
  Unemployment.rate[is.na(Unemployment.rate)] <- 0
  education.enrollment[is.na(education.enrollment)] <- 0
  Urban_population[is.na(Urban_population)] <- 0
  
  # add new categorical variables
  # time_cat
  age_cat <- NA
  age_cat[age <= 3] <- "yong"
  age_cat[age > 3  & age < 13] <- "middle"
  age_cat[age >= 13] <- "old"
  
}) |> change_to_factor()

cleaned_data <- select(cleaned_data,-created_year,-subscribers_for_last_30_days,-subscribers)
return(cleaned_data)
}

2.0 feature selection

Feature selection is a critical step in the machine learning pipeline. It helps in reducing the dimensionality of the dataset, potentially improving the models performance, and providing insights into the relationships between the features and the target variable. In this report, we discuss two distinct methods of feature selection employed in the provided code: a Deviance-based method and a Random Forest-based method.

Deviance-Based Feature Selection

In the Deviance-Based Feature Selection, each feature is individually modeled, and its significance is determined by the difference between null and residual deviance, which essentially captures how much variance the feature explains in the target variable. Features are then ranked by this difference, with those exceeding a score of 50 deemed as influential.

single_variable <- function(data,variable_name,target_variable) {
 
    suppressWarnings({
      
      formula <- as.formula(paste(target_variable, "~", variable_name))
      logic_regression <- train(formula, data = data, method = "glm", family = "binomial")
      
      return(logic_regression)
      
      
    })
  
}




selection_method_1 <- function(data, target_variable) {

  feature_names <- setdiff(colnames(data), target_variable)
  

  result_df <- data.frame(Feature = feature_names, Feature_Score = numeric(length(feature_names)))
  

  for (i in seq_along(feature_names)) {
    col_name <- feature_names[i]
    #print(col_name)
    
    single_variable_model <- single_variable(data, col_name, target_variable)
    summary_result <- summary(single_variable_model)

    null_deviance <- summary_result$null.deviance
    residual_deviance <- summary_result$deviance
      

      difference <- null_deviance - residual_deviance
      

      result_df$Feature_Score[i] <- round(difference, 2)
    
  }
  
  result_df <- result_df[order(result_df$Feature_Score, decreasing = TRUE), ]
  
  return(result_df)
}

result <- selection_method_1(train_data, "income_cat")
# plot the result of feature selection to show the feature score
ggplot(result, aes(x = reorder(Feature, Feature_Score), y = Feature_Score)) +

Random Forest-Based Feature Selection

Random Forest-Based Feature Selection utilizes the ensemble learning technique of Random Forest to evaluate feature importance. This importance, typically gauged by the Mean Decrease in Gini impurity, provides a holistic view of the collective contribution of features to the predictive power of the model. Features surpassing a MeanDecreaseGini value of 10 are selected as salient.

model <- randomForest(income_cat ~ . , data = train_data, ntree = 100)

Both methods offer unique insights into feature relevance. 2.1 Logistic regression

Logistic regression is a classification method that uses a logistic function to model a binary dependent variable. It is a special case of generalized linear regression that predicts the probability of the outcome. The logistic regression model is a linear model, which means that the logit function is a linear combination of the independent variables.

feature engineering for logistic regression model

  1. categorical variables:
    using one hot encoding One-hot encoding is essential for dealing with categorical variables in logistic regression. It transforms non-numeric data, such as gender or location, into binary columns, making them compatible with the model (Ng, 2000).

  2. normalizing numerical variables
    The scale of numerical variables can influence logistic regressions performance. Normalization, such as z-score standardization, brings numerical features within a consistent range, ensuring they contribute evenly to the models output (James et al., 2013).

  3. add interaction terms
    Introducing interaction terms captures complex feature relationships in logistic regression. For instance, when examining the impact of age and income jointly, interaction terms can enhance the models predictive power. However, careful selection is crucial to prevent overcomplicating the model (Hastie et al., 2009).

  4. using L1 regularization to select features
    L1 regularization, also known as Lasso regularization, plays a vital role in feature selection. By driving some feature coefficients to zero, it simplifies the model while retaining important predictors. This enhances model i

References:

Ng, A. Y. (2000). Feature selection, L1 vs.L2 regularization, and rotational invariance. In ICML (Vol. 3, pp.78). James, G., Witten, D., Hastie, T., & Tibshirani, R. (2013). An Introduction to Statistical Learning. Springer. Hastie, T., Tibshirani, R., & Friedman, J. (2009). The Elements of Statistical Learning: Data Mining, Inference, and Prediction. Springer. Tibshirani, R. (1996). Regression shrinkage and selection via the lasso. Journal of the Royal Statistical Society: Series B (Methodological), 58(1), 267-288.

normalise <- function(data){
  # normalise the numerical data excepet target variable income_cat
  # Extract numeric columns (excluding 'income_cat')
  numeric_columns <- colnames(data[, sapply(data, is.numeric) & colnames(data) != 'income_cat'])
  
  scaled_data <- data |>
    mutate_at(vars(numeric_columns), ~ (.-mean(.))/sd(.))
  
  
  return(scaled_data)
}
perform_feature_engineering <- function(data, normalisation = TRUE, selection = 1) {
  
  if (normalisation == TRUE) {
    data <- normalise(data)
  }
  
  if (selection == 1) {
    
 
    data <- data[, c(selected_features_1, "income_cat")]
  }
  
  if (selection == 2) {
 
    data <- data[, c(selected_features_2, "income_cat")]
  }
  
  return(data)
}

2.2 Decision Tree

Decision tree is a classification method that uses a tree-like graph to model the decisions and their possible consequences. It is a supervised learning method that can be used for both classification and regression problems. Not like logistic regression, decision tree is a non-linear model, which means that the decision boundary is not a linear combination of the independent variables. Decision tree is a white box model, which means that the decision process can be explained by the tree structure.

feature engineering for decision tree model

1. do not need to normalize numerical variables

2. do not need to add interaction terms

3. do not need one hot encoding for categorical variables

  1. using Gini index to select features

  2. overfitting: pruning

Both models employ decision trees
- model_3 provides a straightforward approach without feature selection.
- model_4 advances this with feature selection, cross-validation, and hyperparameter tuning for enhanced accuracy and generalization.

Decision Tree Classification Summary:

  • The decision tree primarily differentiates channels based on their subscriber_increase_rate. Those with a higher subscriber rate are predominantly classified as high income (class 1). Conversely: Channels with a lower subscriber rate and fewer uploads (below 95) are almost always categorized as low income (class 0).

  • Among channels with a lower subscriber rate but with more uploads (95 and above), the classification is further influenced by video.views. Those with fewer video views are likely to be low income, while channels with more video views lean towards high income.

To summarize, the subscriber_increase_rate is the most pivotal determinant. For channels with a lower subscriber rate, the number of uploads and video views further define the income classification, with high views indicating a greater likelihood of high income.

Here are the condensed insights based on the decision tree:

  • Subscriber Growth as a Key Predictor: The recent subscriber growth rate is a primary determinant of a channels income class. Channels experiencing a rapid increase in subscribers in the past 30 days are highly likely to belong to the high-income category, highlighting the value of audience acquisition and retention in short bursts.

  • Balancing Upload Frequency and Engagement: For channels with slower subscriber growth, having a higher number of lifetime uploads and a significant number of video views can still position them in the high-income bracket. This underscores the dual importance of content consistency and engagement in driving channel revenue, even if recent subscriber growth is not explosive.

  • Potential of High Viewership: Channels with extensive video views, even in the face of moderate subscriber growth, tend to secure higher income. This insight suggests that a channels ability to draw views and maintain engagement can serve as a powerful lever for monetization, beyond just subscriber numbers.

  • Reflection: It would be beneficial to further tune the decision tree model to minimize overfitting, potentially using techniques like cross-validation. This could help ensure consistent performance across different data sets.

Confusion Matrix Results:

  • Accuracy: The decision tree outperforms the logistic regression by a noticeable margin, with an accuracy of 84.69% compared to 77.55%. This means the decision tree model makes fewer overall mistakes when predicting the outcome.

  • Sensitivity vs.Specificity: Sensitivity represents how well the model identifies the positive class, while specificity represents its ability to identify the negative class. The logistic regression model excels in identifying the positive class with a sensitivity of 80.00%, compared to the decision trees 65.00%. On the other hand, the decision tree is superior in identifying the negative class, with a specificity of 89.74%, as opposed to the logistic regressions 76.92%.

  • Predictive Values: The decision tree is more balanced in its predictions, having both a higher Positive Predictive Value (PPV) and Negative Predictive Value (NPV). This indicates that the decision trees predictions are more reliable regardless of the predicted class.

  • Balanced Accuracy and Kappa: Although both models present similar balanced accuracy values, the decision trees higher Kappa value indicates better consistency and reliability in its predictions compared to the logistic regression.

Summary:

The decision tree seems to be a more robust model overall, with better accuracy and predictive values. Its superior specificity means its less likely to falsely identify a negative instance. However, its sensitivity is lower, which means it might miss out on some positive instances. Conversely, the logistic regression is particularly strong in identifying positive instances but might misclassify negative ones.

get_scaled_df <- function(df, vars_not_to_use) {
  vars_to_scale <- setdiff(names(df), vars_not_to_use)
  scaled_df <- scale(df[, vars_to_scale])
  scaled_df <- as.matrix(scaled_df[complete.cases(scaled_df), ])
  return(scaled_df)
}

get_scaled_center_and_scale <- function(df, vars_not_to_use) {
  vars_to_scale <- setdiff(names(df), vars_not_to_use)
  scaled_df <- scale(df[, vars_to_scale])
  center <- attr(scaled_df, "scaled:center")
  scale <- attr(scaled_df, "scaled:scale")
  return(list(center = center, scale = scale))
}

library(stats)  # Required for the dist function

# we could use different sample_size and k-values to cluster
performHierarchicalClustering <- function(scaled_cluster, df_cluster, sample_size, num_of_cluster) {
  set.seed(123)  # Set a seed for reproducibility
  # Randomly sample a subset of data
  sample_indices <- sample(1:nrow(scaled_cluster), sample_size)
  subset_scaled_cluster <- scaled_cluster[sample_indices, ]
  subset_df_cluster <- df_cluster[sample_indices, ]

  d <- dist(subset_scaled_cluster, method = "euclidean")
  pfit <- hclust(d, method = "ward.D2")
  plot(pfit, labels = subset_df_cluster$channel_type, main = "Cluster Dendrogram")

  num_clusters <- num_of_cluster
  rect.hclust(pfit, k = num_clusters)
  
  # Calculate the Within-Cluster Sum of Squares (WSS)
  clusters <- cutree(pfit, k = num_clusters)
  # Initialize an empty vector to store WSS values for each cluster
  wss <- numeric(num_clusters)
    
  
  # Calculate WSS for each cluster
  for (i in 1:num_clusters) {
    cluster_points <- subset_scaled_cluster[cutree(pfit, k=5) == i, ]
    cluster_center <- colMeans(cluster_points)
    cluster_wss <- sum(rowSums((cluster_points - cluster_center)^2))
    wss[i] <- cluster_wss
    cat(paste("WSS for Cluster", i, ":", cluster_wss, "\n"))
  }
  # Calculate and print the total WSS
  cat("Total WSS (Within-Cluster Sum of Squares):", sum(wss), "\n")

  
  return(list(pfit, subset_df_cluster))
}

hierarchical_result <- performHierarchicalClustering(scaled_cluster, df_cluster, 50,5)

Clustering is unsupervised, so theres no ground truth to evaluate against.

In terms of Visual inspection and domain knowledge, our clustering model does divide the otherwise complex dataset into clusters with their own characteristics based on the input variables we choose(upload freq, channel age, and earning).

We still need to evaluate it using within-cluster sum of squares to provide insight into the quality of the clusters

WSS for Cluster 1 : 65.4246166267765 WSS for Cluster 2 : 145.734674416326 WSS for Cluster 3 : 151.287899983541 WSS for Cluster 4 : 496.189324313617 WSS for Cluster 5 : 91.6056096187777 Total WSS (Within-Cluster Sum of Squares): 950.2421

Interpretation:

  • Smaller cluster-specific WSS values (e.g., Cluster 1,5) indicate that data points within the cluster are closer to each other and the centroid, suggesting a more compact and well-defined cluster.

  • Larger cluster-specific WSS values (e.g., Cluster 4) indicate that data points within the cluster are more spread out, which can suggest a less homogeneous or less well-defined cluster. (Seems There is some conflict with perception because, as explained before cluster 4 clearly has been well grouped with distinctive features. Possible reasons maybe 1. sample-size is not enough. 2. poor performance of the clustering model)

  • The total WSS gives us an overall measure of how well the data points are grouped into clusters. Smaller total WSS values suggest better clustering since the data points are more tightly grouped into their respective clusters.

3.3 K-means

Choosing an Appropriate K Value:

When k=1 the WCSS has the highest value but with increasing k value WCSS value starts to decrease. We choose that value of k (optimal k) from where the graph starts to look like a straight line.

Look for a Change in Slope: Start from the leftmost point on the curve (K=1) and move to the right. Initially, the WSS tends to decrease rapidly. At some point, the rate of decrease will slow down. So the optimal k here is 6.

    #### single variable
single_variable <- function(data,variable_name,target_variable) {

  suppressWarnings({
    # lm
    formula <- as.formula(paste(target_variable, "~", variable_name))
    logic_regression <- train(formula, data = data, method = "glm", family = "binomial")
    
    return(logic_regression)
  })
  
}

    #### roc

plot_ROC <- function (model, data) {
  pred <- predict(model,newdata = data,type = "prob")
  roc_obj <- roc(data$income_cat, pred[,2])
  plot(roc_obj, col = "red", main = "ROC Curve")
  text(0.6, 0.2, labels = paste("AUC  =", round(auc(roc_obj), 3)), col = "red")
}

plot_ROC_classification <- function (roc_obj1, roc_obj2)  {
  plot(roc_obj1, col = "red", main = "ROC Curve Comparison")
  lines(roc_obj2, col = "blue")
  
  
  legend("bottomright", legend = c("Model 1", "*Model 2(improved)"), col = c("red", "blue"), lty = 1)
  
  

  text(0.6, 0.2, labels = paste("AUC Model 1 =", round(auc(roc_obj1), 3)), col = "red")
  text(0.6, 0.1, labels = paste("*AUC Model 2 =", round(auc(roc_obj2), 3)), col = "blue")
  
  
}

    predictions4 <- predict(model_4, 
                            newdata = perform_feature_engineering(validation_data, normalisation = FALSE, selection = 2), 
                            type = "prob")
    roc_obj3 <- roc(validation_data$income_cat, predictions3[,2])
    roc_obj4 <- roc(validation_data$income_cat, predictions4[,2])
    plot_ROC_classification(roc_obj3, roc_obj4)
    
  })
  
  
  ##tab4 
  output$cluster <- renderPlot({
    method <- input$input_cluster_method
    
    if (method == "Hierarchical Clustering") {
      d <- dist(scaled_cluster, method = "euclidean")
      pfit <- hclust(d, method="ward.D2")
      df_cluster <- na.omit(df_cluster)
      princ <- prcomp(scaled_cluster)  # Principal components of scaled_cluster
      nComp <- 2  # First two principal components
      project2D <- as.data.frame(predict(princ, newdata = scaled_cluster)[, 1:nComp])
      hclust.project2D <- cbind(project2D, cluster = as.factor(cutree(pfit, k=5)), channel = df_cluster$channel_type)
      find_convex_hull <- function(proj2Ddf) {
        do.call(rbind,
                lapply(unique(cutree(pfit, k=5)),
                       FUN = function(c) {
                         f <- subset(proj2Ddf, cluster==c);
                         f[chull(f),]
                       }))}
      
      hclust.hull <- find_convex_hull(hclust.project2D)

      ggplot(hclust.project2D, aes(x=PC1, y=PC2)) +
        geom_point(aes(shape=cluster, color=cluster)) +
        geom_text(aes(label=channel, color=cluster), hjust=0, vjust=1, size=3) +
        geom_polygon(data=hclust.hull, aes(group=cluster, fill=as.factor(cluster)),
                     alpha=0.4, linetype=0) + theme(text=element_text(size=20))+
        labs(title = "Cluster Analysis of channel_type")+ 
        theme(text=element_text(size=20))
      
    } else if (method == "Sample Result") {

      
      hierarchical_result <- performHierarchicalClustering(scaled_cluster, df_cluster, input$input_sample_size,5,input$input_cluster_variable)
      s_groups <- cutree(hierarchical_result[[1]], k=5)
      
      print_clusters(hierarchical_result[[2]], s_groups, c("channel_type","age_cat","uploads_freq_cat"))
      
    } else if (method == "K-Means") {
      
      
      kmeans_result <- kmeans(scaled_cluster, centers = 6)
      cluster_assignments <- factor(kmeans_result$cluster)
      df_cluster$cluster <- cluster_assignments
      var_a <- input$input_variableA
      var_b <- input$input_variableB
      kmeans_data <- data.frame(a = df_cluster[[var_a]], 
                                b = df_cluster[[var_b]], 
                                Cluster = factor(df_cluster$cluster))

      ggplot(kmeans_data, aes(x = a, y = b, fill = Cluster)) +
        geom_tile() +
        scale_fill_manual(values = 1:6) +
        labs(x = input$input_variableA, y = input$input_variableB, title = "K-means Clustering Results (K = 6)")+ 
        theme(text=element_text(size=20), axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1))
    }

  })
  
 
  
}
